import pandas as pd
import altair as alt
data = pd.read_csv("denver-1.nov.csv")
data = data.dropna()
alt.data_transformers.disable_max_rows()
Out[17]:
DataTransformerRegistry.enable('default')

First, I decided to filter the data by district. I also removed the NaN values from the outcomes, since there were a large number of entries that did not contain any information on the outcome. While this may skew the data analysis, it will still make the interpretation more interesting, since nearly half of the entries contained NaN values. I decided to aggregate the data based on the outcome. It would be expected that the rate of arrests is not very different from district to district, since we do not expect the people to be inherently more or less likely to be arrested.

In [26]:
alt.Chart(data).mark_bar().encode(
    x=alt.X("district", sort="x"),
    y=alt.Y("count()"),
    color=alt.Color('outcome', scale=alt.Scale(scheme='tableau10')),
    tooltip=["outcome","count()"]).properties(
    width=800,
    height=300)
Out[26]:

As we can see here, the main variation between districts is the number of total stoppages, rather than the types of stoppages. While there are certainly some outliers, the overall tendency is a pretty even distribution of outcomes. It appears that around a third of the stoppages, within each district, are arrests, another third are citations, and the last third are warnings. In District 6, we see a lot more arrests than any other outcome, as there are more arrests than the other two outcomes combined. And in District's 3 and 5, there are almost as many citations given than any other outcome combined. Still, the data does not tell us the full story. Looking at this without any prior knowledge may suggest that District 6 is too strict, and should arrest fewer people during stops. But this claim cannot be confirmed, as we do not know what was going on during these stoppages. The data is not very descriptive - probably for good reason, considering privacy issues - so we cannot make a very strong claim. Overall, the data seems to follow a similar pattern, in that there is a pretty even distribution of outcomes during police stoppages. In the future, it would be interesting to consider other cities, and how they may look under the same lense. Additionally, it would be interesting to look at how these proportions have changed historically. Further research should consider several cities (of varying size, location, and demographic) and consider the fact that public relations with police have changed over time. Can this analysis be applied to other US cities, or even other countries?
